              <table id="EditorialReviewsPanel" class="ReviewSection" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%"><tr><td>
	
                <DIV class="ReviewHeading">Amazon.com:</DIV>
                <span id="Label1"><I>Reading the Bible Again for the First Time</I> is Marcus Borg's  follow-up to <I>Meeting Jesus Again  for the First Time</I>. Like his earlier book, this one is written for lay  people whose faith has been frustrated by their misapprehension that  fundamentalism's claim to be the one true faith is valid. Borg, a professor of  religion at Oregon State University, describes an alternative to  fundamentalists' so-called "literal" readings of scripture. (He believes that  such "literal-factual" readings do not live up to that description, and that the  limitations of such readings have alienated many people who would otherwise  remain part of the church.) Borg calls his alternative "historical-metaphorical"  reading, a way of "taking the Bible seriously without taking it literally."  <I>Reading the Bible</I> begins with a history of recent conflicts regarding  biblical interpretation. Borg navigates the minefields of his subject with  sensitivity and precision, explaining, for example, the important distinction  between evangelical and fundamentalist readings of the Bible. He then offers  historical-metaphorical readings of some key texts from both the Hebrew Bible  and the New Testament. Throughout, Borg writes with calm assurance and respect  for those who would disagree with him. <I>Reading the Bible</I> is a credible  guide to the project it names. It is a faithful exercise of reason, undertaken  to help Christians hear more clearly the many voices recorded in the Bible.  <I>--Michael Joseph Gross</I></span>
              
</td></tr></table>
              <table id="CustomerReviewsPanel" class="ReviewSection" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%"><tr><td>
	
                <DIV class="ReviewHeading">Customer reviews:</DIV>
                
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Utterly disappointing</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>1</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>2</span>
                      /
                      <span>2</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-05-20</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>After reading Borg's book I came away tremendously disappointed with how poorly he reasons for his particular point of view and would not recommend this book to anyone seeking scholarly information on reading the Bible. 
<br />	His book is divided into three main sections: the first deals with foundational issues on the subject and the fact that we all read the Bible through various lenses. This is the most important section of the book as the other two stand or fall on the integrity of the first. His second section deals with the Hebrew Bible, i.e., the Old Testament, and his last section deals with the New.
<br />	In the first section, Borg discusses four different reasons why the modern culture has departed from traditional interpretations of reading the Bible. As I see it, his fourth reason is the most specific in dealing with how he will treat Scripture throughout the remainder of the book so I will limit my comments to it. 
<br />	He states that postmodernity has taught us that "metaphors and metaphorical narratives can be profoundly true even if they are not literally or factually true" (p. 17). But what is important to remember here is that, as Christian philosopher William Lane Craig has said, a metaphor must have a literal meaning in order to make any sense at all. If I were to say, "It's raining cats and dogs outside" then, unless there is a literal truth behind the metaphor, i.e., it's really raining hard outside, then the metaphor is meaningless. 
<br />	The problem with Borg's interpretation is that he rarely, if ever, gives any literal meaning behind the metaphor. Thus, his metaphors are meaningless and Borg's interpretations are meaningless as well. 
<br />	For instance, Borg claims to believe that Jesus rose from the dead and that he is our Lord today. However, in Borg's view, there is no post-Easter Jesus; Jesus' body was simply a rotting corpse. But unless Borg can give a literal meaning for his belief that "Jesus rose from the dead," his own beliefs are not metaphors, they're nonsense! 
<br />	Another very important point to mention is that Borg reads the Bible with a relentless anti-supernatural bias.  He asks, "...do virgin births, multiplying loaves and fish, and changing water into wine ever happen anywhere?" Borg answers this question by saying, "...what I cannot do as a historian is to say that Jesus could do such things even though nobody else has ever been able to. Thus I regard these as purely metaphorical narratives" (p. 47). 
<br />	So Borg makes it clear that the plain meaning of the biblical text is not his primary method of interpretation, but rather, it is an anti-supernatural presupposition he brings to the text which determines how he reads it. Yet, remarkably, this methodology he employs is blatantly contrary to the advice he gives his students on how to interpret a biblical text. He says, "I often tell my students that reading well involves listening well-seeking to hear what the text is saying to us and not simply absorbing the text into what we already think" (pp. 30-31).
<br />	But is Borg following his own advice here? Since he admits that he follows a principle of hermeneutics which overrides a clear reading of the text, i.e., his own anti-supernatural presuppositions, then it certainly seems he is not. This leaves the reader with the glaring notion that Borg really hasn't thought out his conclusions too neatly!
<br />	Borg also has a major problem with the Christian exclusivism taught in John 14:6: ""I am the way, and the truth, and the life; no one comes to the Father except through me."
<br />	In his view, Jesus is not saying that faith in him is the only way to get to heaven, but rather, that we must all die to an old way of being and be born into a new way of being-as Jesus was-to get close to God. Since all religions of the world incorporate this belief into their doctrinal system, then Christ's way can be known in every religion.
<br />	Not only does Borg believe that all religions contain the pathway of Jesus to get close to God, but he also considers it strange we ever thought otherwise. Regarding this he says, "...as if one entered new life by believing certain things to be true, or as if the only people who can be saved are those who know the word `Jesus.' Thinking that way virtually amounts to salvation by syllables" (pp. 216-17).
<br />	The most blatant problem with this belief is that it is self-refuting. First of all, even Borg believes that the way of Jesus entails our death to an old way of living and our subsequent birth to a new way of living. But in order for this to happen we must believe in certain propositional knowledge as well: namely, we must die to an old way of living and be born again to a new one. Also, Borg decries the traditional Christian position as being a "salvation by syllables" but Borg is doing the very same thing. His belief in a new life also requires uttering syllables and so if uttering syllables is so utterly detestable, then Borg falls on his own sword!
<br />	However, is there anything really wrong with propositional knowledge of God being required to help us draw closer to him? At first blush, it almost seems foolish to simply ask the question as it becomes impossible for us to describe God-let alone believe in his existence-without propositional knowledge. It seems that Borg's view would mean that it should be possible for even a man like Adolf Hitler to become a saint in heaven because the belief, "we cannot get close to God if we brutally torture Jews," requires  propositional knowledge of God. Would Borg ever dream of saying that the above statement is "strange" because it both requires we believe certain things to be true and also requires us to utter syllables and because of this, we can then treat Jews any way we want? 
<br />	The fact is, propositional knowledge of God is required in order for us to grow closer to him and Borg's assault on it is what seems strange. If Borg has a problem with the integrity of certain propositional statements, then he should attack that statement in particular and not retreat into both self-refuting and ridiculous attacks on propositional knowledge in general.
<br />	In short, the God that Borg wants us to conceive of in this book is a God who, ultimately, cannot be described by propositional statements, but only experienced. Since Borg makes the propositional statement that God only works through natural means, he makes God's existence superfluous as there does not seem to be much of a difference to Borg in whether God truly exists or not. 
<br />	But because Borg believes that Christ can change lives even while stripping him of his divine authority to do so, he turns Christ into nothing more than a crutch. And since any other crutch is just as good as our crutch, Marcus Borg has turned Christ into a placebo-with no real power to do anything outside of the believer's imagination.
<br />Thus, the conclusion of this book is not informative or enlightening in any way as propositional knowledge is required to actually inform. Rather, it seems that Borg's conclusion is incoherent.
<br />
<br /></span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Unsettling, but important</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
