                    </div>
                    <span>Most people seem to either hate this book or love it. I think I do both; but I realize the parts I love are those I agree with and the parts I "hate" are those in sharp conflict with what I thought was true. At the very least this book will make the Christian think, if he is willing to stretch a little. Personally I still like to think that Jesus will come again, and I certainly believe that life on earth will end sometime in the future. And I believe in prayer, which is not addressed sufficiently in this book.  Professor Borg's most important writing is his Epilogue, where he summarizes the whole thing as " Love God" and "Love your Neighbor". As Jesus stated and showed, any way you turn it, that is what it is all about. </span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">A challenging, well written book.</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>1</span>
                      /
                      <span>2</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-02-28</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>This really is an extraordinary book.  Since I'm not a biblical scholar (except in the sense of being an occasional amateur one) I can't sensibly talk about the depth of the scholarship.  It does seem very impressive.
<br />
<br />
<br />The book is a very easy one to read; Borg is an excellent communicator and manages to cover a great deal of material in a very accessible manner.  I found it at times rather confronting, because it made me re-evaluate a number of issues to do with my faith that had been left undisturbed for years.  That was especially so of the conclusion which is a very stirring, and confronting, call to action.
<br />
<br />One particular problem that I had with the book was that Borg seems to view Jesus as a man who knew God intimately.  I'm still not completely clear how exactly how the human Jesus relates to the divine Christ.  But to take away a star for that would be overkill, especially as the problem is probably mine.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">It Pains Me Deeply To Pan This Book</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>2</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>4</span>
                      /
                      <span>5</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-02-05</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>I like everything this book says.  I like Mr. Borg's heart.  But, by the end of the Hebrew Scriptures section I had to admit that Borg had been pretty intellectually dishonest.  Borg does a great job covering the anti-empire voice of scripture in the books of Moses and in the Prophets, but he all but ignores the rather pro-empire historical books like the Samuels, Kings and Chronicles.   There is a dynamic tension in scripture between the voice that Borg chooses to hilite in this book, and its spirited opposition, also found throughout scripture.  Borg would have significantly strengthened his case if he addressed the books less compatible with his thesis and put them within a context of dynamic tension with the books he chooses to focus on.  I find this particularly unfortunate because we live in a time when a voice like Borg is most needed.  The unfortunate truth is that too many conspicuous silences lead me to believe that Borg is not being completely honest.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Excellent Teaser.....</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>4</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>6</span>
                      /
                      <span>6</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-01-03</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>This small book is a high-level overview of the philosophical divide between literalist "Bible-believing" Christians and those who believe that biblical precepts should be believed but interpreted metaphorically. In addition, Borg presents the basic thesis of the "Historical Jesus" movement.  
<br />
<br />The book is a good introduction for those who are unfamiliar with the core debate. However, those who have already read some of the other books by Marcus Borg and John Dominic Crossan may find this work elementary and sweeping.    
<br />
<br />Although a challenge to established religious dogma is always controversial, what is not is Borg's ability to break down sophisticated concepts into user-friendly language and to fluidly compress vast material into a manageable but comprehensive summary.  In this, he offers new hope to those alienated from the church by providing an alternative path back into meaningful and authentic spiritual inquiry.   
<br /></span>
                  
              
